# MIDAS Infrastructure Rules (`infra.mdc`)

## Scope

Applies whenever working with files under `deploy/` or `ai_gateway/`.

---

## Rule: No Direct Internet Container Pulls in AWS

**AWS has no internet access.** The MIDAS VPC (`vpc-0c4d673f3e95a93eb`) has no Internet Gateway and no NAT Gateway. Container images cannot be pulled directly from public registries (Docker Hub, ghcr.io, quay.io, etc.) at runtime inside AWS.

### Mandatory pattern — all container images

1. **Build/pull on Jenkins.** The Jenkins pipeline runs outside the VPC and has outbound internet access. Pull or build every required image there during the CI/CD build stage.
2. **Push to ECR.** After pulling/building, tag and push the image to the MIDAS ECR registry in `us-east-1`.
3. **Reference ECR in AWS.** All ECS task definitions, EKS pod specs, Helm charts, and Terraform configurations must reference the ECR URI — never a public registry URI.

### Example flow

```
# Jenkins build stage (has internet)
docker pull some-public-image:tag
docker tag  some-public-image:tag <account>.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/midas/<name>:tag
aws ecr get-login-password | docker login --username AWS --password-stdin <account>.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com
docker push <account>.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/midas/<name>:tag

# ECS / EKS (no internet — references ECR only)
image: <account>.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/midas/<name>:tag
```

### Stop and ask the user before

- Using a public registry URI in any task definition, pod spec, Helm value, or Terraform resource.
- Adding `imagePullPolicy: Always` against a non-ECR registry.
- Proposing a runtime image-pull mechanism that does not go through ECR.
